[assistant] Built a minimal RP2040 breakout in `index.circuit.tsx` using only local/JLCPCB-imported parts, with USB-C, a status LED on `GPIO25`, external QSPI flash, the required 12 MHz crystal, decoupling, and `routingDisabled` on the board root.

- The board in `index.circuit.tsx` places an imported `RP2040`, imported USB-C receptacle, imported LED, imported crystal, and imported passive JLCPCB parts; no tscircuit registry components are used.
- I modeled the breakout headers directly as generic `chip` footprints so the board exposes power, reset, several GPIOs, and ADC pins without depending on registry packages.
- USB D+ and D- are connected through 27 ohm series resistors, CC pins have 5.1k pulldowns, `RUN` has a 10k pull-up, the LED has a 1k resistor, and the RP2040 power rails are tied into local decoupling nets.
- I used a simple local SOIC-8 flash placeholder in `index.circuit.tsx` for the mandatory QSPI flash interface so the RP2040 design is electrically coherent enough for generation and review.
- I ran `tsci build --site --use-cdn-javascript --ignore-errors`, which generated output in `dist/`, and `tsci snapshot`, which produced `__snapshots__/index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg` and `__snapshots__/index.circuit-schematic.snap.svg`.
- Assumption: “minimal breakout” means a compact reference-style board for visualization and iteration, not a fully production-ready Pico-equivalent design with regulator, boot button, SWD header, and tuned USB layout.
